ðŸ”¹ What is FLSM?

        FLSM = Fixed Length Subnet Masking
        
        Matlab: saare subnets ka size same hota hai (equal number of hosts).
        
        Har subnet me equal IP addresses distribute kiye jaate hain.

ðŸ”¹ Why FLSM?

        Easy calculation
        
        Easy to manage
        
        Lekin IP addresses waste hote hain agar kisi subnet me kam devices ho

ðŸ”¹ Steps to Calculate FLSM

Find total IPs in given network.

        Eg: 192.168.1.0/24 â†’ Total = 2^(32-24) = 2^8 = 256 IPs

Decide how many subnets you need.

        Example: Chahiye 4 subnets

Find subnet bits.

        Formula = 2^n â‰¥ number of subnets
        
        Yaha: 2^2 = 4 â†’ so n = 2 bits

New subnet mask.

        Original mask: /24 (255.255.255.0)
        
        Add 2 bits â†’ /26 (255.255.255.192)

Subnet size.

        2^(32-26) = 2^6 = 64 IPs per subnet

ðŸ”¹ Example:

        Network = 192.168.1.0/24
        Need = 4 subnets
        
        ðŸ‘‰ Subnetting:
        
                | Subnet No. | Network Address | Usable Range                  | Broadcast Address |
                | ---------- | --------------- | ----------------------------- | ----------------- |
                | 1          | 192.168.1.0     | 192.168.1.1 â€“ 192.168.1.62    | 192.168.1.63      |
                | 2          | 192.168.1.64    | 192.168.1.65 â€“ 192.168.1.126  | 192.168.1.127     |
                | 3          | 192.168.1.128   | 192.168.1.129 â€“ 192.168.1.190 | 192.168.1.191     |
                | 4          | 192.168.1.192   | 192.168.1.193 â€“ 192.168.1.254 | 192.168.1.255     |

âœ… Each subnet has 64 IPs (62 usable).
âœ… All subnets equal â†’ this is FLSM.

ðŸŽ¯ One-Line Summary

FLSM = Divide the network into equal-sized subnets (same subnet mask, same host count per subnet).



What is VLSM?

        Variable Length Subnet Masking
        
        Matlab: alag-alag subnets ka size alag ho sakta hai, need ke hisaab se.
        
        Yaha pe IP addresses waste nahi hote jaise FLSM me hote the.

ðŸ‘‰ FLSM = equal subnets (same mask).
ðŸ‘‰ VLSM = flexible subnets (different mask, need based).

ðŸ”¹ Why VLSM?

        Har department / network ki alag requirement hoti hai.
        
        Example:
        
                Development = 60 PCs
                
                Management = 30 PCs
                
                HR = 12 PCs
        
        Agar FLSM karenge â†’ sabko barabar subnet milega (62 usable), IP waste hoga.
        
        Agar VLSM karenge â†’ har ek ko apni zarurat ke hisaab se IP milega.

ðŸ”¹ Steps of VLSM

        Total network ka IP block identify karo.
        
                Example: 192.168.1.0/24 â†’ total 256 IPs
        
        Requirement list banao (bade se chhote tak).
        
                Dev = 60 hosts
                
                Mgmt = 30 hosts
                
                HR = 12 hosts
        
        Har requirement ke liye sabse chhota possible subnet mask choose karo.
        
        Subnets ko allocate karo without overlap.

ðŸ”¹ Example Solve (192.168.1.0/24)
Step 1: Dev needs 60 hosts

        Formula = 2^n â€“ 2 â‰¥ hosts
        
        2^6 â€“ 2 = 62 â†’ OK
        
        So subnet = /26 (64 IPs)
        
        Allocate â†’ 192.168.1.0 â€“ 192.168.1.63

Step 2: Mgmt needs 30 hosts

        2^5 â€“ 2 = 30 â†’ OK
        
        Subnet = /27 (32 IPs)
        
        Next block â†’ 192.168.1.64 â€“ 192.168.1.95

Step 3: HR needs 12 hosts

        2^4 â€“ 2 = 14 â†’ OK
        
        Subnet = /28 (16 IPs)
        
        Next block â†’ 192.168.1.96 â€“ 192.168.1.111

ðŸ”¹ Final Allocation Table
        | Department | Needed Hosts | Subnet Mask           | Network Address | Usable Range                 | Broadcast     |
        | ---------- | ------------ | --------------------- | --------------- | ---------------------------- | ------------- |
        | Dev        | 60           | /26 (255.255.255.192) | 192.168.1.0     | 192.168.1.1 â€“ 192.168.1.62   | 192.168.1.63  |
        | Mgmt       | 30           | /27 (255.255.255.224) | 192.168.1.64    | 192.168.1.65 â€“ 192.168.1.94  | 192.168.1.95  |
        | HR         | 12           | /28 (255.255.255.240) | 192.168.1.96    | 192.168.1.97 â€“ 192.168.1.110 | 192.168.1.111 |

ðŸŽ¯ One-Line Summary (Shortcut)

VLSM = allocate different subnet sizes to different departments/networks based on their actual need â†’ no IP wastage.
